q1: It reminds of the game you play as a child where you whisper something to the person next to you and see if the message stays the same at the end of the chain.

It's a complex "truth in sending" scenario: three players get to report accurately or selfishly on a picked hidden number. Two players can see the "real" # (first one who picked it at random and third one who finally reports it) but a "middleman" can only report what the picker claims the # was. Because the compensation for these  three is solely dependent upon how big a # the third player's "final" report is, there is no rationale for reporting the actual number picked, other than honesty. If all three players report a high number they all get paid highest. Note that two other non-particpating players (4th and 5th) receive SMALLER payments based on the picked number versus reported number.
q3: Not sure why the compensation scheme was structured as it was (notably what the 4th and 5th "passive" players receive). It made calculating the actual impact of selections more difficult, with the possibility of miscalculation. Maybe this was part of the experiment.
